revention and emergency planning/response programs help Marathon effectively manage the hazards posed by the regulated substance to the Terminal employees, surrounding public, and environment. The covered process is regulated by the EPA RMP regulation 40 CFR Part 68, as well as the OSHA Process Safety Management standard 29 CFR 1910.119. The following accident prevention program elements are in place at the Niles LP Terminal:

1) Employee Participation;
2) Process Safety Information;
3) Process Hazard Analysis (PHA);
4) Standard Operating Procedures;
5) Training;
6) Contractors;
7) Pre-startup Safety Review;
8) Mechanical Integrity with Preventive Maintenance;
9) Hazardous Work Permits;
10)Management of Change;
11)Incident or Potential Catastrophic Event Investigation;
12)Emergency Response;
13)Compliance Audits; and
14)Trade Secrets.

These fourteen (14) individual elements of this prevention program work together to prevent accidental chemical releases. The Niles LP Terminal and its employees are committed to the standards required by these management programs. In addition to the above elements, MPLX also has specific prevention measures that are employed as part of the Terminal's operating procedures and engineering and administrative controls to help prevent, identify, contain/control, and reduce the consequences of a release. These are summarized as follows:

General Risk Reduction and Safety Measures:

-Engineering and construction in accordance with recognized industry and company standards;
-Equipment properly designed with protection from overpressure (pressure safety relief valves, etc.);
-Updated technical drawings, Piping & Instrument Diagrams and Process/Block Flow Diagrams;
-Operating systems monitored and controlled by trained Operators;
-Redundant control systems;
-Manual shutdown devices for critical systems;
-Scheduled inspection and testing of safety devices;
-Limited/secured facility access;
-Regular safety meetings and safety awareness programs;
